\paragraph*{Remark: Why a Symmetric Three-Point Design for all $(u,r)$.}
Under the USW near-field model (single-path, narrowband), each antenna element has the
same amplitude $|\beta|$, while the phase varies with location
\[
h(x;\eta)=\beta\,\exp\!\Big\{j\frac{2\pi}{\lambda}\Big(xu-\frac{1-u^2}{2r}x^2\Big)\Big\},\qquad
\eta=[u,r]^\top .
\]
This corresponds to the regime $a/r\!\ll\!1$, so elementwise amplitude variations
$1/r(x)$ are negligible and absorbed into $\beta$. Hence all localization information
resides in the phase derivatives
\[
\partial_u\phi(x;\eta)\ \propto\ x+\tfrac{u}{r}x^2,\qquad
\partial_r\phi(x;\eta)\ \propto\ x^2,
\]
i.e., the ``slope'' and ``curvature'' features. Translating the array toward the target
does not increase SNR but induces a nonzero cross-covariance
$\operatorname{cov}(X,X^2)$, which decreases
\[
\Delta=\operatorname{var}(X)\operatorname{var}(X^2)-\operatorname{cov}^2(X,X^2)
\]
and enlarges both $\mathrm{CRB}_u$ and $\mathrm{CRB}_r$. A symmetric geometry enforces
$\operatorname{cov}(X,X^2)=0$, fully decoupling angle and range, and yields
\[
\operatorname{Tr}(\mathrm{CRB})=\kappa\!\left[
\frac{\alpha(u,r)}{\operatorname{var}(X)}+
\frac{\beta(u,r)}{\operatorname{var}(X^2)}\right],
\]
where $\alpha(u,r),\beta(u,r)>0$ depend on $(u,r)$ but not on geometry. Optimizing this
over distributions supported on $[-a,a]$ gives, by moment-extremal arguments, a symmetric
three-atomic solution supported on $\{-a,0,+a\}$; only the weights depend on $(u,r)$.
